column49: I have to say I really do not like the changes to Scholastic.  I do not like how teachers can't set their own due dates.  And there are no paper orders anymore.  I loved having the flexibility to send home orders when it worked for my classroom.  Now I send them home, and the website tells me when they have to order by (sometimes it's just days after I've sent them home).  I have always been very satisfied with Scholastic... but this year feels very different and VERY offputting.

column49: I know that the ordering of Scholastic books has changed during the last few years.  While I know change is hard, I'm not exactly liking the new ordering system.  Some of the parents do not feel comfortable ordering books online and, therefore choose not to participate.  As a teacher,  I did not mind collecting the orders and money, if it was easier for the parents/students.  I'm also used to a monthly order and not seasonal.  I would always try to send out my orders the first week of the month.  It seemed to work well.

column49: I do not like the new book club format. It is not accessible to all families and has made it so students are unable to purchase books with allowance/savings because they only have cash. Some families in our community don't receive regular paychecks and don't have access to a bank account to buy their student's books since it is now required that they order online. The prices on the books have also become quite inaccessible especially with taxes being added and the cost of holiday gift books has made it next to impossible for teachers to purchase gift books for students on a budget. If it weren't for bonus points I had saved up for bigger items that no longer exist in the bonus points catalog, I wouldn't have been able to get my students a book for Christmas, which has been my tradition for over 15 years. column49: The recent changes made to Scholastic Book Clubs are not as teacher-friendly as being touted. The inability to place classroom orders at will is a huge inconvenience. Also, the lack of paper ordering is inconsiderate and burdensome to parents who are not tech savvy. It is much more frustrating as a teacher to have to keep track of which child ordered which books personally rather than being able to place individual orders for children in my class on the website. I understand the desire to have parents place their own orders, but leave it up to the teacher to decide if she/he will implement online ordering only rather than making the decision for thousands of teachers and families.  With these changes, it is less likely our school continue ordering with Scholastic.

column49: Your book selection seems to have gone down in recent years.  I used to get almost all of my classroom library books from Scholastic.  Now, whenever I hear about a new book, even though the Scholastic Book Clubs website is the first place I search, it's almost never available and I end up ordering from somewhere else.  For years, right after the ALA awards were announced in January, you would have many, many of the books available through Scholastic.  As far as I can tell, you haven't had the 2023 Newbery winner (Freewater) available at all (I check every month).  PLEASE broaden your selection or I will continue having to purchase my classroom library books elsewhere.  In addition, I used to recommend Scholastic Book Clubs to all my colleagues, and I have stopped doing that.
